A GRANDEUR THAT WAS ROME
They moan, passing upon the clouds, horned and capricorned, the Trumpeted with the tusked, the lion maned, the giantantlered, stouter and crawler, rodent, ruminant and pachyderm, all their moving moaning multitude, murderers of the sun.
Onward to the dead sea they tramp to drink, unslaked and with horrible gulpings,  the salt somnolent inexhaustible flood.
Trumpery insanity.

What is the age of the soul?

The voices blend and fuse in clouded silence:
silence that is the infinite of space: and swiftly, silently the soul wafted over regions of cycles of generations that have lived.
A region where grey twilight ever descends, never falls on wide sagegreen pasturefields, shedding her dusk, scattering a perennial dew of stars. 

Joyce knows better than most:
Utopia is neither serene, clean nor a dream:
It is as painful perhaps  to be awakened from a vision as to be born.

There are sins or (let us call them as the world calls them) evil memories which are hidden away by humanity in the darkest places of the heart but they abide there and wait. Many may suffer their memory to grow dim, let them be as though they had not been and all but persuade themselves that they were not or at least were otherwise.
Yet a chance word will call them forth suddenly and they will rise up to confront them in the most various circumstances, a vision or a dream, or while timbres and harp soothe their senses or amid the cool silver tranquility of the evening or at the feast, at midnight, when they are now filled with wine. Not to insult over them will the vision come over one that lies under her wrath, not for vengeance to cut them off from the living but shrouded in the piteous vesture of the past, silent, remote, reproachful.

O and the sea
the sea
crimson sometimes like fire and the glorious sunsets and the fig trees in the Alameda gardens
yes and
all the queer little streets and the pink and blue and yellow houses and the rosegardens and the jessamine and geraniums and cactuses and Gibraltar...
where I was a Flower of the mountains
yes...
and yes I said yes I will Yes.

